ce:section.ce:para:
The optimized BO@CDs/BTB sensing system's analytical performance was thoroughly assessed by measuring fluorescence at different urea concentrations. As shown in Fig. 3
                        A, the dual-emission response displayed concentration-dependent behavior, with opposing fluorescence intensity changes: a gradual decrease at 612 nm and a simultaneous increase at 442 nm. This “Double-response-Reverse” ratiometric pattern creates a self-calibrating detection mechanism. Quantitative analysis showed a strong linear relationship between the fluorescence intensity ratio (F442/F612) and urea concentrations ranging from 10.0 to 100.0 μM (Fig. 3B). The calibration curve, described by the equation F442/F612 = 0.147[C] + 0.097, exhibited a high correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.9937). The method's sensitivity, calculated using the LOD formula (3σ/k), was 2.86 μM. When compared to existing methods (Table 1
                        ), this ratiometric fluorescence approach stands out for its simplicity, wide linear range, and high sensitivity. These results highlight the system's reliability as an effective tool for accurate urea quantification.
